%[text] # Workflow Cluster Determination
%[text] 
%[text] This workflow shows how to determine and look for Clusters in your dataset. 
%[text] All of the codes are based on the use of Voronoi cells. In the paper "Detecting and extracting clusters in atom probe data: A simple, automated method using Voronoi cells" P.Felfer, A.V. Ceguerra, S.P. Ringer, J.M. Cairney Utramicroscopy 150 (2015) 30-36 a deeper description about the algorithm is presented.
%[text] For the calculation, the user needs a decomposed pos file.
%%
%[text] ## Determine the clusters
%[text] The clusterDetermination function calculates the voronoi Volume in combination with the delaunay triangulation. The Kolmogorov - Smirnov test as described in the paper above is also performed.
%[text] As an output, the user gets 4 different tables. In the table clusterParameter are general parameter stored about the cluster Determination stored, e.g. logical values for the Kolmogorov-Smirnov test (1 = passed, 0 = failed), the cluster percentage, Nmin and the clusterCutOff volume. The next table clusteredAtoms stores the pos data of the atoms that are clustered. clusterPosVol is the clusterPos Variable with a new column with the calculated Voronoi Volume for each cell. The last output table contains the randomVolumes used for the calculation. 
clusterPos = pos(pos.ion == 'D H',:); %[control:editfield:9f54]{"position":[29,34]}
[clusterParameter, clusteredAtoms, clusterPosVol, randomVolumes]= clusterDetermination(clusterPos,pos); %[output:9bef70f1] %[output:26490eec] %[output:736f8737]
  %[control:button:2e43]{"position":[1,2]}

%%
%[text] ## Store data from Multiple clusterDetermination from one dataset
%[text] The user can also run multiple clusterDetermination with one dataset but different elements and store all of the results in one table;
clusterElement = "D H"; % Choose the element %[control:editfield:225d]{"position":[18,23]}
clusterParameter = addvars(clusterParameter, clusterElement) % add an additional row to clusterParameter for distinguishing between different calculations %[output:4058e075]
% clusterParaSample = clusterParameter; % run this line after the first clusterDetermination
clusterParaSample = [clusterParaSample;clusterParameter]; % run this line after you created clusterParaSample and you performed the second clusterDetermination with another element
  %[control:button:0952]{"position":[1,2]}
%%
%[text] ## More detail with a closer look at the function contained by clusterDetermination
%[text] The clusterDetermination function runs a series of custom written functions that give more detail about the data set. 
%[text] ### Voronoi Volume analysis
%[text] with this function, the voronoi volume is calculated for a given data set 
[numClustered, clusterCutoff, histCounts, experimentalVolumes, randomVolumes] = voronoiVolumeAnalysis(clusterPos, pos);
%%
%[text] ### clusterIdentification
%[text] clusterIdentification calculates the number of clusters and their corresponding cluster Index after Voronoi Tesselation and Dealaunay triangulation
%[text] Dataset:
volThreshORpos = clusterCutoff; % or pos
[clusterIdx, numClusters] = clusterIdentification(clusterPos,volThreshORpos,experimentalVolumes.expVol);
%[text] random Dataset:
[randomClusterIdx, randomNumClusters] = clusterIdentification(randomVolumes,volThreshORpos,randomVolumes.randVol);
%%
%[text] ### Analyse the cluster size
%[text] at Nmin atoms, it is a cluster
expClusterSizes = histcounts(clusterIdx, numClusters);
ranClusterSizes = histcounts(randomClusterIdx, randomNumClusters);
Nmin = clusterSizeAnalyse(expClusterSizes,ranClusterSizes);
%%
